@* THE SILENT DIVERGENCE decision 168 CLOSED, found by PROBING the eleven spec 3 non-goals ADR 0003
   declared closed (register defect A8).

   @ref on an element INSIDE a @foreach row used to compile at exit 0 with NO diagnostic. Decision
   132's mapping is "the reference IS the element's name", and under a region that name is declared
   in the row's OWN local function:

     function createR(r) { const row = document.createElement('li'); … return row; }
     …
     listen(_el3, 'click', async () => { await row.focus(); });     <-- FREE VARIABLE

   Driven under happy-dom with listen() wrapped so the swallowed rejection is visible, this exact
   source gave:

     {"active":"","err":"ReferenceError: row is not defined"}

   while the unmodified baseline/ElemRef.Blazor control through the same harness gave
   {"active":"box","err":null}. The only difference is region scope.

   NOT HOISTED, REFUSED. `let row;` at mount scope assigned inside createR is LAST-ASSIGNED-WINS, and
   list() never re-runs create() for a persisting key, so after a reorder the name would point at a
   different element than Blazor's capture does -- a subtler divergence than the one being fixed. It
   needs a Blazor reorder oracle before it can ship (register S5).

   Supported/Gate/RefOutsideRow.razor is THE SAME FILE with the @ref moved off the row: it compiles,
   so this fixture refuses for the region and for nothing else.

   VALID BLAZOR: dotnet build of this source in a real Blazor WebAssembly project succeeds. *@
<ul id="list"><button id="add" @onclick="Add">add</button>@foreach (Row r in _rows)
{
    <li @key="r.Id" @ref="row"><span class="lbl">@r.Label</span></li>
}</ul><button id="go" @onclick="Focus">go</button>

@code {
    record Row
    {
        public int Id { get; set; }
        public string Label { get; set; } = "";
    }

    private List<Row> _rows = new List<Row>();
    private int _next = 1;
    private ElementReference row;

    private void Add()
    {
        Row r = new Row();
        r.Id = _next;
        r.Label = "task " + _next;
        _next = _next + 1;
        _rows.Add(r);
    }

    async Task Focus() { await row.FocusAsync(); }
}
